ka Local Government|volume=XIII|issue=2|page=15|location=Juneau|publisher=[[Alaska Department of Commerce, Community and Economic Development|Alaska Department of Community and Regional Affairs]]|date=January 1974}}</ref>\n\n<!-- Area -->| area_magnitude                  = \n| area_footnotes                  = <ref name=\"CenPopGazetteer2016\">{{cite web|title=2018 U.S. Gazetteer Files|url=https://www2.census.gov/geo/docs/maps-data/data/gazetteer/2018_Gazetteer/2018_gaz_place_02.txt|publisher=United States Census Bureau|accessdate=Jul 1, 2019}}</ref>\n| area_total_km2                  = 112.71\n| area_land_km2                   = 68.76\n| area_water_km2                  = 43.95\n| area_total_sq_mi                = 43.52\n| area_land_sq_mi                 = 26.55\n| area_water_sq_mi                = 16.97\n<!-- Population -->| population_as_of                = [[2010 United States Census|2010]]\n| population_footnotes            = <ref name=\"census2010\" />\n| population_total                = 219\n| population_density_km2          = 3.26\n\n<!-- General information -->| timezone                        = [[Alaska Time Zone|Alaska (AKST)]]\n| utc_offset                      = -9\n| timezone_DST                    = AKDT\n| utc_offset_DST                  = -8\n| elevation_footnotes             = \n| elevation_m                     = 11\n| elevation_ft                    = 36\n| coordinates                     = {{coord|59|16|42|N|158|37|23|W|region:US-AK|display=inline}}\n| postal_code_type                = [[ZIP code]]\n| postal_code                     = 99555\n| area_code                       = [[Area code 907|907]]\n| area_code_type                  = [[North American Numbering Plan|Area code]]\n| blank_name                      = [[Federal Information Processing Standard|FIPS code]]\n| blank_info                      = 02-01420\n| blank1_name                     = [[Geographic Names Information System|GNIS]] feature ID\n| blank1_info                     = {{GNIS 4|1398091}}\n| website                         = {{URL|https://www.commerce.alaska.gov/dcra/DCRAExternal/community/Details/c47614a0-11f3-498d-b60d-89eee14e54af}}\n| footnotes                       = \n| pop_est_as_of                   = 2018\n| pop_est_footnotes               = <ref name=\"USCensusEst2018\"/>\n| population_est                  = 224\n| population_density_sq_mi        = 8.44\n| unit_pref                       = Imperial\n| name                            = \n}}\n'''Aleknagik''' ({{IPAc-en|\u0259|\u02c8|l|\u025b|k|n|\u0259|\u0261|\u026a|k}} {{respell|\u0259|LEK|n\u0259-gik}}; ''Alaqnaqiq'' in [[Yupik language|Central Yup'ik]]) is a second class city in the [[Dillingham Census Area, Alaska|Dillingham Census Area]] of the [[Unorganized Borough, Alaska|Unorganized Borough]] of the U.S. state of [[Alaska]]. The population was 219 at the [[2010 United States Census|2010 census]],<ref name=\"census2010\">{{cite web|url=http://factfinder.census.gov/bkmk/table/1.0/en/DEC/10_DP/DPDP1/1600000US0201420|archive-url=https://archive.today/20200212110753/http://factfinder.census.gov/bkmk/table/1.0/en/DEC/10_DP/DPDP1/1600000US0201420|url-status=dead|archive-date=2020-02-12|title=Profile of General Population and Housing Characteristics: 2010 Demographic Profile Data|publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]], American FactFinder|accessdate=2012-11-14}}</ref> down from 221 in 2000.\n\n==Geography==\nAleknagik is located at {{Coord|59|16|42|N|158|37|23|W|type:city}} (59.278362, -158.622928)<ref name=\"GR1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/geographies/reference-files/time-series/geo/gazetteer-files.html|publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]]|accessdate=2011-04-23|date=2011-02-12|title=US Gazetteer files: 2010, 2000, and 1990}}</ref> (Sec. 31, T010S, R055W, Seward Meridian), in the Bristol Bay Recording District.\n\nAleknagik is located at the head of the [[Wood River (Alaska)|Wood River]] on the southeast end of Lake Aleknagik, {{convert|16|mi|km}} northwest of [[Dillingham, Alaska|Dillingham]]. The city is named after [[Aleknagik Lake]].\n\nAccording to the [[United States Census Bureau]], the city has a total area of {{convert|107.5|km2|order=flip}}, of which {{convert|63.5|km2|order=flip}} is land and {{convert|44.0|km2|order=flip}}, or 40.89%, is water.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://factfinder2.census.gov/bkmk/table/1.0/en/DEC/10_DP/G001/1600000US0201420| title=Geographic Identifiers: 2010 Demographic Profile Data (G001): Aleknagik city, Alaska| publisher=U.S. Census Bureau, American Factfinder| accessdate=October 8, 2015}}{{dead link|bot=medic|date=April 2020}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref>\n\n== Climate ==\nAleknagik's climate is similar to that of nearby [[Anchorage]] and [[Dillingham, Alaska#Climate|Dillingham]], having a typical [[subarctic climate]] ([[K\u00f6ppen climate classification]]: '''Dfc'''). Fog and low clouds are common during July and August, and may preclude access. The lake and river are ice-free from June through mid-November.  A weather station was operated between 1958 and 1973; however the climate data has many missing observations and appears slightly irregular, with March in many years being colder than February. The smoothed data, however, shows March slightly warmer:\n\n{{Weather box \n|location = Aleknagik\n|single line = Y\n| Jan record high F = 49\n| Feb record high F = 45\n| Mar record high F = 52\n| Apr record high F = 53\n| May record high F = 71\n| Jun record high F = 88\n| Jul record high F = 88\n| Aug record high F = 78\n| Sep record high F = 70\n| Oct record high F = 61\n| Nov record high F = 47\n| Dec record high F = 45\n|year record high F =  \n| Jan high F = 20.6\n| Feb high F = 27.9\n| Mar high F = 27.5\n| Apr high F = 37.0\n| May high F = 50.1\n| Jun high F = 61.2\n| Jul high F = 66.0\n| Aug high F = 63.0\n| Sep high F = 56.8\n| Oct high F = 41.2\n| Nov high F = 29.3\n| Dec high F = 21.7\n| year high F =  \n|Jan mean F = 12.4\n|Feb mean F = 18.9\n|Mar mean F = 16.6\n|Apr mean F = 28.7\n|May mean F = 41.1\n|Jun mean F = 50.9\n|Jul mean F = 56.1\n|Aug mean F = 53.1\n|Sep mean F = 48.2\n|Oct mean F = 33.5\n|Nov mean F = 22.2\n|Dec mean F = 14.2\n|year mean F = \n| Jan low F = 4.1\n| Feb low F = 9.8\n| Mar low F = 5.7\n| Apr low F = 20.3\n| May low F = 32.0\n| Jun low F = 40.6\n| Jul low F = 46.1\n| Aug low F = 43.2\n| Sep low F = 39.5\n| Oct low F = 25.7\n| Nov low F = 15.0\n| Dec low F = 6.6\n| year low F = \n| Jan record low F = \u221244\n| Feb record low F = \u221235\n| Mar record low F = \u221236\n| Apr record low F = \u221215\n| May record low F = 11\n| Jun record low F = 23\n| Jul record low F = 31\n| Aug record low F = 28\n| Sep record low F = 22\n| Oct record low F = -4\n| Nov record low F = \u221220\n| Dec record low F = \u221227\n|year record low F =  \n| precipitation colour = green\n| Jan precipitation inch = 1.84\n| Feb precipitation inch = 2.06\n| Mar precipitation inch = 2.41\n| Apr precipitation inch = 2.98\n| May precipitation inch = 3.12\n| Jun precipitation inch = 2.87\n| Jul precipitation inch = 2.77\n| Aug precipitation inch = 5.14\n| Sep precipitation inch = 4.81\n| Oct precipitation inch = 2.82\n| Nov precipitation inch = 2.55\n| Dec precipitation inch = 2.79\n| year precipitation inch =  \n| Jan snow inch = 10.4\n| Feb snow inch = 14.9\n| Mar snow inch = 12.5\n| Apr snow inch = 7.8\n| May snow inch = 1.3\n| Jun snow inch = 0.0\n| Jul snow inch = 0.0\n| Aug snow inch = 0.0\n| Sep snow inch = 0.0\n| Oct snow inch = 2.3\n| Nov snow inch = 9.2\n| Dec snow inch = 8.4\n| year snow inch = 66.9\n|source 1 = <ref>{{cite web\n|url=https://wrcc.dri.edu/cgi-bin/cliMAIN.pl?ak0201|title=ALEKNAGIK, ALASKA - Climate Summary}}</ref>\n|date=July 2018\n}}\n\n==History and culture==\nWood River and Aleknagik Lake have been used historically as summer fish camps. The spelling of the Yupik word \"Aleknagik\" has been disputed, because Yupik was an unwritten language. The name was described by the resident Yako family in 1930 as meaning \"Wrong Way Home\", because Nushagak River residents returning to their homes upriver would sometimes become lost in the fog and find themselves swept up the Wood River with the tide, inadvertently arriving at Aleknagik Lake.\n\nRecorded history may not define the exact place of Aleknagik, and various reports have reported the original site with the name \"Alaqnaqiq\" as far to the south near entrance to the Wood River. James Van Stone, an anthropologist who traveled to [[Saint Petersburg]] and read diaries of the Russian explorers from 1867, noted that explorers traveled to \"Aleknagik Lake\" (in a spelling that is Russian but sounds out to Aleknagik).\n\nIn 2005, the Alaska Department of Natural Resources applied to own the waterways and compiled an extensive history of the area in their application (see Links below).\n\nThe 1929 U.S. Census found 55 people living in the \"Wood River village\" area to the south. During 1930, there were five families living on the shores of the lake year-round, the Waskeys, Polleys, Hansons, Yakos, and Smiths. A log cabin territorial school was built on the south shore of the lake in 1933, and Josie Waskey was the first teacher. Attracted by the school, other facilities, and plentiful fish, game and timber, a number of families from the [[Goodnews Bay, Alaska|Goodnews]], [[Togiak, Alaska|Togiak]], and Kulukak areas relocated to Aleknagik. A post office was established in March 1937, with Mrs Mabel M. Smith as postmaster.<ref>Dickerson, Ora B., \"120 Years of Alaska Postmasters, 1867-1987\", Cammarata, Carl J., Scotts, Michigan, 1989, p 18.</ref>  A two-story framed school with a teacher apartment was constructed in 1938. By 1939, Aleknagik had 78 residents, over 30 buildings, and a small sawmill. In the late 1940s, a [[Seventh-day Adventist Church|Seventh-day Adventist]] mission and school were established on the north shore. During the 1950s, a [[Moravian Church|Moravian]] church and a [[Russian Orthodox Church|Russian Orthodox]] church were built in Aleknagik, and over 35 families lived along the lake. In 1959, the state constructed a {{convert|25|mi|km|adj=on}} road connecting the south shore to Dillingham. The road was passable only during the summer months, until the late 1980s when it was upgraded and maintained year-round. The city was incorporated in 1973. Over 24 additional square miles were annexed to the city in April 2000.\n\nIn the mid-1950s, Moravian church members formed a colony on the north shore of the lake, across from the post office. The Moravian pastor and his wife's family built homes there and remain in the community.\n\nIn the late 19th century there were about 200 people in Aleknagik and the other Wood River villages. Varied illnesses killed most of the residents of the villages. The few survivors moved out of the area. In fall of 1930, there was one Yupik family living at the top of the Wood River in Aleknagik, and the village grew to about 40 people by 1931. By 1940, Aleknagik had over 30 buildings, including a community school, church, and small sawmill. The local religious mission school, run by [[Seventh-day Adventists]], brought several new families to Aleknagik. Other families came to the village because of the territorial school.\n\nIn 1938, a territorial school was constructed in Aleknagik. During this period, a Moravian church, a Russian Orthodox church and a Seventh-day Adventist mission school were established in the community. In 1959, the State of Alaska constructed a {{convert|22|mi|km|adj=on}} road connecting Aleknagik to [[Dillingham, Alaska|Dillingham]].\n\nThe Aleknagik Traditional Council, a federally-recognized tribe, is located in the community.\n\nIn August 2010, an airplane carrying former Senator [[Ted Stevens]] [[2010 Alaska Turbo Otter crash|crashed near Alegnagik]], resulting in the death of Stevens and four others.\n\n==Demographics==\n{{US Census population|align=left\n|1940= 78\n|1950= 153\n|1960= 181\n|1970= 128\n|1980= 154\n|1990= 185\n|2000= 221\n|2010= 219\n|estyear=2018\n|estimate=224\n|estref=<ref name=\"USCensusEst2018\">{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/programs-surveys/popest/data/tables.2018.html|title=Population and Housing Unit Estimates|accessdate=June 4, 2019}}</ref>\n|footnote=U.S. Decennial Census<ref name=\"DecennialCensus\">{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/programs-surveys/decennial-census.html|title=Census of Population and Housing|publisher=Census.gov|accessdate=June 4, 2015}}</ref>\n}}\nAleknagik first appeared on 1940 U.S. Census as an unincorporated village.<ref>https://www2.census.gov/prod2/decennial/documents/33973538v1ch11.pdf</ref> It appeared as Aleknagik Lake (uninc.) on the 1960 census, and neighboring village of Aleknagik Mission showed 50 residents (for a combined total area of 231).<ref>https://www2.census.gov/prod2/decennial/documents/37721577v1p3ch2.pdf</ref> In 1970,<ref>https://www2.census.gov/prod2/decennial/documents/1970a_ak-01.pdf</ref> it appeared again simply as Aleknagik and was incorporated in 1973.\n\nAs of the census<ref name=\"GR2\">{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov |publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]] |accessdate=2008-01-31 |title=U.S. Census website }}</ref> of 2000, there were 221 people, 70 households, and 52 families residing in the city.  The population density was 19.1 people per square mile (7.4/km\u00b2).  There were 107 housing units at an average density of 9.3 per square&nbsp;mile (3.6/km\u00b2).  The racial makeup of the city was 13.57% [[Race (United States Census)|White]], 81.90% [[Race (United States Census)|Native American]], 1.36% from [[Race (United States Census)|other races]], and 3.17% from two or more races.  1.36% of the population were [[Race (United States Census)|Hispanic]] or [[Race (United States Census)|Latino]] of any race.\n\nThere were 70 households out of which 41.4% had children under the age of 18 living with them, 48.6% were married couples living together, 11.4% had a female householder with no husband present, and 24.3% were non-families. 17.1% of all households were made up of individuals and 2.9% had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older.  The average household size was 3.16 and the average family size was 3.62.\n\nIn the city, the age distribution of the population shows 37.1% under the age of 18, 9.0% from 18 to 24, 29.9% from 25 to 44, 16.3% from 45 to 64, and 7.7% who were 65 years of age or older.  The median age was 28 years. For every 100 females, there were 121.0 males.  For every 100 females age 18 and over, there were 131.7 males.\n\nThe median income for a household in the city was $22,750, and the median income for a family was $30,625. Males had a median income of $29,583 versus $75,487 for females. The [[per capita income]] for the city was $10,973.  About 21.7% of families and 40.8% of the population were below the [[poverty line]], including 49.0% of those under the age of eighteen and 21.4% of those sixty five or over.\n\n==Public services==\nThe majority of residents (49 homes) have household plumbing, and most use individual wells. 12 homes do not have water or sewer service \u2013 some haul water from the community center, and a few are served by a spring water catchment system. Septic tanks, leechate fields and public sewage lagoons are used for sewage disposal. The North Shore uses eleven shared residential effluent pumps (REP units) which discharge into a piped system. There are three landfill sites. The North Shore landfill is being relocated; the South Shore landfill has an incinerator but is unfenced. A third landfill is located {{convert|2|mi|km}} from the South Shore, on the West side of the Aleknagik-Dillingham road.  Electricity is provided by Nushugak Electric Cooperative. Local hospitals or health clinics include North Shore Health Clinic (842-5512), South Shore Health Clinic (842-2185) or Kanakanak Hospital in Dillingham.  Both, North and South Shore Clinics are Primary Health Care facilities. Aleknagik is classified as a highway village, it is found in EMS Region 2I in the Bristol Bay Region. Emergency Services have limited highway, air and satellite access. Emergency service is provided by volunteers and a health aide  Auxiliary health care is provided by Aleknagik First Responders Group (907-842-2085); or Kanakanak Hospital in Dillingham (25 road miles).\n\nThere is one school located in the community, Aleknagik School, operated by the [[Southwest Region School District]].<ref>\"[http://www.swrsd.org/home/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=52&Itemid=133 Aleknagik].\" [[Southwest Region School District]]. Retrieved on March 26, 2017.</ref> It is attended by 26 students.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://education.alaska.gov/DOE_Rolodex/SchoolCalendar/Home/SchoolDetails/450020#|title=Aleknagik School - Alaska Public Schools Database|website=education.alaska.gov|language=en|access-date=2017-05-01}}</ref>\n\n==Economy and transportation==\nMany residents participate in commercial and subsistence activities on the Bristol Bay coast during the summer. 33 residents hold commercial fishing permits. Trapping is also an important means of income. Most families depend to some extent on subsistence activities to supplement their livelihoods. Salmon, freshwater fish, moose, caribou, and berries are harvested. Poor fish returns and prices since 1997 have significantly affected the community.\n\nAleknagik is the only village in the region coming close to a road link with Dillingham; a {{convert|25|mi|adj=on}} road connects to the south shore of Aleknagik Lake from which the city is within walking distance. The [[Aleknagik Airport|\"New Aleknagik\" airport]] is a State-owned {{convert|2070|ft|m|adj=mid|-long}} by {{convert|90|ft|m|adj=mid|-wide}} gravel airstrip located on the north shore, and regular flights are scheduled through Dillingham. The north shore of the lake is not road accessible; residents use skiffs to travel to town on the south shore. Moody's Aleknagik Seaplane Base, also on the north shore, accommodates float planes. There are two additional airstrips, the public Tripod Airport, a {{Convert|1250|ft|adj=on}} turf-gravel airstrip located {{convert|2|mi|0}} southeast of Aleknagik, and the Adventist Mission School Airport, a {{convert|1200|ft|adj=on}} gravel/dirt airstrip with a crosswind runway. The State owns and operates a {{convert|100|ft|adj=on}} dock on the north shore of Aleknagik Lake. A [[breakwater (structure)|breakwater]], barge landing, boat launch ramp and boat lift are available on the north shore. Vehicles, skiffs, ATVs and snowmachines are the most frequent means of local transportation.\n\nSales tax in the community is 5%, and there is also a 5% accommodations tax. There is no property tax.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Portal|Alaska}}\n* [https://www.commerce.alaska.gov/dcra/DCRAExternal/community/Details/c47614a0-11f3-498d-b60d-89eee14e54af Aleknagik] at the Community Database Online from the [[Alaska Department of Commerce, Community and Economic Development|Alaska Division of Community and Regional Affairs]]\n* Maps from the [[Alaska Department of Labor and Workforce Development]]: [https://web.archive.org/web/20160304190022/http://labor.alaska.gov/research/alari/images/maps/6_7_9map.pdf 2000], [https://web.archive.org/web/20151222121041/http://labor.alaska.gov/research/census/placemaps/01420.pdf 2010]\n\n{{Coord|display=title|59.275|-158.625}}\n{{Dillingham Census Area, Alaska}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Cities in Alaska]]\n[[Category:Cities in Dillingham Census Area, Alaska]]\n[[Category:Cities in Unorganized Borough, Alaska]]\n[[Category:History of the Alaska Province of the Moravian Church]]\n[[Category:Road-inaccessible communities of Alaska]]\n", "name_user": "Menchi", "label": "safe", "comment": "langtags", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Aleknagik,_Alaska"}
{"title_page": "Alakanuk, Alaska", "text_new": "{{short description|City in Alaska, United States}}\n{{Infobox settlement\n|official_name            = Alakanuk\n|native_name              = Alarneq\n     | native_name_lang        = esu\n|settlement_type          = [[City (Alaska)|City]]\n|nickname                 = \n|motto                    = <!-- Images -->\n|image_skyline            = File:AUK-Aerial Map.jpg\n|image_caption            = Alakanuk Airport\n|imagesize                = 300px\n|image_flag               = \n|image_seal               = <!-- Maps -->\n|pushpin_map  = Alaska\n|pushpin_map_caption  = Location in Alaska\n\n<!-- Location -->\n|subdivision_type         = Country\n|subdivision_name         = United States\n|subdivision_type1        = [[U.S. state|State]]\n|subdivision_name1        = [[Alaska]]\n|subdivision_type2        = [[List of boroughs and census areas in Alaska|Census area]]\n|subdivision_name2        = [[Kusilvak Census Area, Alaska|Kusilvak]]\n|government_footnotes     = \n|government_type          = \n|leader_title             = [[Mayor]]\n|leader_name              = Mary Ayunerak\n|leader_title1            = [[Alaska Senate|State senator]]\n|leader_name1             = [[Donny Olson]] ([[Democratic Party (United States)|D]])\n|leader_title2            = [[Alaska House of Representatives|State rep.]]\n|leader_name2             = [[Neal Foster]] (D)\n|established_title        = [[Municipal corporation|Incorporated]]\n|established_date         = October 28, 1969<ref>{{Cite book|title=1996 Alaska Municipal Officials Directory|location=[[Juneau]]|publisher=Alaska Municipal League/[[Alaska Department of Commerce, Community and Economic Development|Alaska Department of Community and Regional Affairs]]|date=January 1996|page=20}} (though an earlier source states November 5, 1973;  see {{Cite journal|title=Directory of Borough and City Officials 1974|journal=Alaska Local Government|volume=XIII|issue=2|page=14|location=Juneau|publisher=[[Alaska Department of Commerce, Community and Economic Development|Alaska Department of Community and Regional Affairs]]|date=January 1974}})</ref>\n\n<!-- Area -->\n|area_magnitude           = \n|area_footnotes           = <ref name=\"CenPopGazetteer2016\">{{cite web|title=2018 U.S. Gazetteer Files|url=https://www2.census.gov/geo/docs/maps-data/data/gazetteer/2018_Gazetteer/2018_gaz_place_02.txt|publisher=United States Census Bureau|accessdate=Jul 1, 2019}}</ref>\n|area_total_km2           = 108.26\n|area_land_km2            = 82.93\n|area_water_km2           = 25.33\n|area_total_sq_mi         = 41.80\n|area_land_sq_mi          = 32.02\n|area_water_sq_mi         = 9.78\n\n<!-- Population -->\n|population_as_of         = [[2010 United States Census|2010]]\n|population_footnotes     = <ref name=\"2007popest\">{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/popest/cities/tables/SUB-EST2007-04-02.csv|title=Annual Estimates of the Population for Incorporated Places in Alaska|publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]]|date=2008-07-10|accessdate=2008-07-14|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080912000504/http://www.census.gov/popest/cities/tables/SUB-EST2007-04-02.csv|archive-date=2008-09-12|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n|population_total         = 677\n|timezone                 = [[Alaska Time Zone|Alaska (AKST)]]\n|utc_offset               = -9\n|timezone_DST             = AKDT\n|utc_offset_DST           = -8\n|elevation_footnotes      = \n|elevation_m              = 1\n|elevation_ft             = 3\n|coordinates              = {{Coord|62|41|5|N|164|38|43|W|region:US_type:city|display=inline,title}}\n|postal_code_type         = [[ZIP code]]\n|postal_code              = 99554\n|area_code                = [[Area code 907|907]]\n|area_code_type           = [[North American Numbering Plan|Area code]]\n|blank_name               = [[Federal Information Processing Standard|FIPS code]]\n|blank_info               = 02-01200\n|blank1_name              = [[Geographic Names Information System|GNIS]] feature ID\n|blank1_info              = {{GNIS4|1398042}}\n|website                  = {{URL|https://www.commerce.alaska.gov/dcra/DCRAExternal/community/Details/ce7e59f5-2ed0-4555-8468-0a18a3a36191}}\n|footnotes                = \n|pop_est_as_of = 2018\n|pop_est_footnotes = <ref name=\"USCensusEst2018\"/>\n|population_est = 773\n|population_density_sq_mi = 24.14\n|unit_pref = Imperial\n|population_density_km2 = 9.32\n}}\n\n'''Alakanuk''' {{small|(ah-LUCK-uh-nuck)}} ({{lang-esu|Alarneq}}) is a second class city in the [[Kusilvak Census Area, Alaska|Kusilvak Census Area]] of the [[Unorganized Borough, Alaska|Unorganized Borough]] in the western part of the U.S. state of [[Alaska]]. As of the [[United States Census, 2010|2010 census]], the population of the city was 677, up from 652 in 2000.\n\n==Location and Climate==\nAlakanuk is located at 62.688890\u00b0 North, 164.61528\u00b0 West (Sec. 14, T030N, R082W, Seward Meridian).<ref name=\"GR1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/geographies/reference-files/time-series/geo/gazetteer-files.html|publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]]|accessdate=2011-04-23|date=2011-02-12|title=US Gazetteer files: 2010, 2000, and 1990}}</ref> Alakanuk is located in the Bethel [[Recording District (Alaska)|Recording District]].\n\nAlakanuk is located at the east entrance of Alakanuk Pass, the major southern channel of the [[Yukon River]], {{convert|15|mi|km}} from the Bering Sea. It is part of the Yukon Delta National Wildlife Refuge. It lies {{convert|8|mi|km}} southwest of Emmonak, approximately {{convert|162|mi|km}} northwest of Bethel. It is the longest village on the lower Yukon - the development stretches over a {{convert|3|mi|km|adj=on}} area along the Pass. Approximately 25 homes along the bank are being threatened by erosion.\n\nThe climate of Alakanuk is subarctic, averaging {{convert|60|in|mm}} of snowfall and {{convert|19|in|mm}} of total precipitation per year. Temperatures range from between {{convert|-25|to|79|\u00b0F|\u00b0C}}. Heavy winds are frequent during the fall and winter. The Yukon River is used as an ice road during freeze-up, from November through May.\n\nAccording to the [[United States Census Bureau]], the city has a total area of {{convert|41.0|sqmi|km2}}, of which, {{convert|32.4|sqmi|km2}} of it is land and {{convert|8.7|sqmi|km2}} of it (21.14%) is water.\n\n==History and culture==\nAlakanuk is a Yup'ik word meaning \"wrong way\" or \"mistake village\", aptly applied to a village on this maze of watercourses. The village was first reported by G.R. Putnam of the U.S. Coast & Geodetic Survey in 1899. It was originally settled by a Yup'ik shaman named Anguksuar and his family. A Catholic mission school was built near the village. A post office was established in 1946. In 1948, the school was relocated to St. Mary's, and many families moved from the old school site to Alakanuk. It incorporated as a second-class city in 1969.\n\nA federally recognized tribe is located in the community\u2014the Village of Alakanuk.\n\n==Demographics==\n{{US Census population|align=left\n|1940= 61\n|1950= 140\n|1960= 278\n|1970= 414\n|1980= 522\n|1990= 544\n|2000= 652\n|2010= 677\n|estyear=2018\n|estimate=773\n|estref=<ref name=\"USCensusEst2018\">{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/programs-surveys/popest/data/tables.2018.html|title=Population and Housing Unit Estimates|accessdate=June 4, 2019}}</ref>\n|footnote=U.S. Decennial Census<ref name=\"DecennialCensus\">{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/programs-surveys/decennial-census.html|title=Census of Population and Housing|publisher=Census.gov|accessdate=June 4, 2015}}</ref>\n}}\nAlakanuk first appeared on the 1940 U.S. Census as the unincorporated native village of \"Alaganuck.\"<ref>https://www2.census.gov/prod2/decennial/documents/33973538v1ch11.pdf</ref> It returned as Alakanuk in 1950<ref>https://www2.census.gov/prod2/decennial/documents/41601749v2p51-54ch2.pdf</ref> and every successive census to date (2010)<ref>https://www.census.gov/prod/cen2010/cph-1-3.pdf</ref>. It formally incorporated in 1969.\n\nAs of the census<ref name=\"GR2\">{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov |publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]] |accessdate=2008-01-31 |title=U.S. Census website }}</ref> of 2000, there were 652 people, 139 households, and 118 families residing in the city.  The population density was 20.2 people per square mile (7.8/km\u00b2).  There were 160 housing units at an average density of 4.9 per square&nbsp;mile (1.9/km\u00b2).  The racial makeup of the city was 1.99% [[Race (United States Census)|White]], 95.40% [[Race (United States Census)|Native American]], 0.15% [[Race (United States Census)|Asian]], and 2.45% from two or more races.\n\nThere were 139 households out of which 59.7% had children under the age of 18 living with them, 57.6% were married couples living together, 12.9% had a female householder with no husband present, and 15.1% were non-families. 10.8% of all households were made up of individuals and 2.9% had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older.  The average household size was 4.69 and the average family size was 5.19.\n\nIn the city, the age distribution of the population shows 44.6% under the age of 18, 12.9% from 18 to 24, 21.9% from 25 to 44, 13.7% from 45 to 64, and 6.9% who were 65 years of age or older.  The median age was 20 years. For every 100 females, there were 111.0 males.  For every 100 females age 18 and over, there were 109.9 males.\n\nThe median income for a household in the city was $26,346, and the median income for a family was $26,500. Males had a median income of $19,792 versus $32,500 for females. The [[per capita income]] for the city was $6,884.  About 32.5% of families and 33.8% of the population were below the [[poverty line]], including 34.1% of those under age 18 and 25.8% of those age 65 or over.\n\n==Facilities, Utilities, and Health Care==\nThe City operates the water and piped sewer system and the central watering point. Approximately 90% of homes are connected. There is a sewage lagoon available for individuals to dump their [[Bucket toilet|honey bucket]]s. The City Council is the policy-making body for the utility. Water is derived from the Alakanuk Slough; it is treated, stored in a tank, and piped to most of the community. In 1998, 83 homes, the school and teachers' housing were connected to a new piped system. New facilities include a water treatment plant, heated 300,000-gal. water storage tank, vacuum sewage plant, sewage lagoon, Arctic piping, and household plumbing. A new subdivision is currently underway, and nine homes will be connected to the piped utilities. The city has funding from DEC for service connections to 20 homes. Ten homes have been moved from the erosion zone on the river bank and are ready for service. The city is planning to move an additional 10 homes. AVCP is building a 9-home subdivision, including water and sewer mains and service connections, for occupancy in 2002. The city completed a feasibility study for service area 7, which is the area across the river, and would like to obtain funding to make this expansion. The landfill is reported as inactive. Electricity is provided by AVEC. Local hospitals or health clinics include Alakanuk Health Clinic and Pearl E. Johnson Sub-Regional Clinic in Emmonak.  Alakanuk Health Clinic is a Primary Health Care facility. Alakanuk is classified as an isolated village, located in EMS Region 7A in the Yukon/Kuskokwim Region. Emergency Services have coastal and air access. Emergency service is provided by a health aide\n\n==Education==\nK-12 students attend Alakanuk School, operated by the [[Lower Yukon School District]].\n\n==Economy and Transportation==\nAlakanuk experiences a seasonal economy. 76 residents hold commercial fishing permits. Many have gill net permits, and set net fishermen sell their salmon to Seattle fish buyers. Poor fish returns since 1998 have significantly affected the community. Government employment and retail businesses provide limited year-round employment. Salmon, beluga whale, seal, moose and rabbit provide food sources. Some residents trap. Many residents travel to Emmonak to shop and attend social events and basketball tournaments.\n\n[[Alakanuk Airport]], a State-owned 2,200' long by 55' wide gravel airstrip, is available. An airport relocation project is underway, due to erosion. Grant Aviation, Hageland Aviation and Tanana Air Service offer passenger flight service. Alakanuk is easily accessible from the Yukon River and Bering Sea by barge and riverboat. Most passengers and mail arrive by air. There are no roads connecting Alakanuk with other population centers in the region, but ice roads are used in winter. Snowmachines and boats are used for local travel.\n\nTaxes:\tSales: 4%, Property: None, Special: None\n\n==Notable people==\n* [[Segundo Llorente|Father Segundo Llorente]], a [[Society of Jesus|Jesuit priest]] born in [[Spain]], was elected to the [[Alaska House of Representatives]] in 1960 as a [[write-in candidate]] while stationed in Alakanuk.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Portal|Alaska}}\n* [https://www.commerce.alaska.gov/dcra/DCRAExternal/community/Details/ce7e59f5-2ed0-4555-8468-0a18a3a36191 Alakanuk] at the Community Database Online from the [[Alaska Department of Commerce, Community and Economic Development|Alaska Division of Community and Regional Affairs]]\n* Maps from the [[Alaska Department of Labor and Workforce Development]]: [https://web.archive.org/web/20160304194705/http://labor.alaska.gov/research/alari/images/maps/6_26_6map.pdf 2000], [https://web.archive.org/web/20151222120351/http://labor.alaska.gov/research/census/placemaps/01200.pdf 2010]\n\n{{Kusilvak Census Area, Alaska}}\n{{Authority control}}\n[[Category:Cities in Alaska]]\n[[Category:Cities in Kusilvak Census Area, Alaska]]\n[[Category:Cities in Unorganized Borough, Alaska]]\n[[Category:Road-inaccessible communities of Alaska]]\n[[Category:Yukon River]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|City in Alaska, United States}}\n{{Infobox settlement\n|official_name            = Alakanuk\n|native_name              = Alarneq\n|settlement_type          = [[City (Alaska)|City]]\n|nickname                 = \n|motto                    = <!-- Images -->\n|image_skyline            = File:AUK-Aerial Map.jpg\n|image_caption            = Alakanuk Airport\n|imagesize                = 300px\n|image_flag               = \n|image_seal               = <!-- Maps -->\n|pushpin_map  = Alaska\n|pushpin_map_caption  = Location in Alaska\n\n<!-- Location -->\n|subdivision_type         = Country\n|subdivision_name         = United States\n|subdivision_type1        = [[U.S. state|State]]\n|subdivision_name1        = [[Alaska]]\n|subdivision_type2        = [[List of boroughs and census areas in Alaska|Census area]]\n|subdivision_name2        = [[Kusilvak Census Area, Alaska|Kusilvak]]\n|government_footnotes     = \n|government_type          = \n|leader_title             = [[Mayor]]\n|leader_name              = Mary Ayunerak\n|leader_title1            = [[Alaska Senate|State senator]]\n|leader_name1             = [[Donny Olson]] ([[Democratic Party (United States)|D]])\n|leader_title2            = [[Alaska House of Representatives|State rep.]]\n|leader_name2             = [[Neal Foster]] (D)\n|established_title        = [[Municipal corporation|Incorporated]]\n|established_date         = October 28, 1969<ref>{{Cite book|title=1996 Alaska Municipal Officials Directory|location=[[Juneau]]|publisher=Alaska Municipal League/[[Alaska Department of Commerce, Community and Economic Development|Alaska Department of Community and Regional Affairs]]|date=January 1996|page=20}} (though an earlier source states November 5, 1973;  see {{Cite journal|title=Directory of Borough and City Officials 1974|journal=Alaska Local Government|volume=XIII|issue=2|page=14|location=Juneau|publisher=[[Alaska Department of Commerce, Community and Economic Development|Alaska Department of Community and Regional Affairs]]|date=January 1974}})</ref>\n\n<!-- Area -->\n|area_magnitude           = \n|area_footnotes           = <ref name=\"CenPopGazetteer2016\">{{cite web|title=2018 U.S. Gazetteer Files|url=https://www2.census.gov/geo/docs/maps-data/data/gazetteer/2018_Gazetteer/2018_gaz_place_02.txt|publisher=United States Census Bureau|accessdate=Jul 1, 2019}}</ref>\n|area_total_km2           = 108.26\n|area_land_km2            = 82.93\n|area_water_km2           = 25.33\n|area_total_sq_mi         = 41.80\n|area_land_sq_mi          = 32.02\n|area_water_sq_mi         = 9.78\n\n<!-- Population -->\n|population_as_of         = [[2010 United States Census|2010]]\n|population_footnotes     = <ref name=\"2007popest\">{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/popest/cities/tables/SUB-EST2007-04-02.csv|title=Annual Estimates of the Population for Incorporated Places in Alaska|publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]]|date=2008-07-10|accessdate=2008-07-14|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080912000504/http://www.census.gov/popest/cities/tables/SUB-EST2007-04-02.csv|archive-date=2008-09-12|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n|population_total         = 677\n|timezone                 = [[Alaska Time Zone|Alaska (AKST)]]\n|utc_offset               = -9\n|timezone_DST             = AKDT\n|utc_offset_DST           = -8\n|elevation_footnotes      = \n|elevation_m              = 1\n|elevation_ft             = 3\n|coordinates              = {{Coord|62|41|5|N|164|38|43|W|region:US_type:city|display=inline,title}}\n|postal_code_type         = [[ZIP code]]\n|postal_code              = 99554\n|area_code                = [[Area code 907|907]]\n|area_code_type           = [[North American Numbering Plan|Area code]]\n|blank_name               = [[Federal Information Processing Standard|FIPS code]]\n|blank_info               = 02-01200\n|blank1_name              = [[Geographic Names Information System|GNIS]] feature ID\n|blank1_info              = {{GNIS4|1398042}}\n|website                  = {{URL|https://www.commerce.alaska.gov/dcra/DCRAExternal/community/Details/ce7e59f5-2ed0-4555-8468-0a18a3a36191}}\n|footnotes                = \n|pop_est_as_of = 2018\n|pop_est_footnotes = <ref name=\"USCensusEst2018\"/>\n|population_est = 773\n|population_density_sq_mi = 24.14\n|unit_pref = Imperial\n|population_density_km2 = 9.32\n}}\n\n'''Alakanuk''' (ah-LUCK-uh-nuck) (''Alarneq'' in [[Central Yup'ik language|Central Yup'ik]]) is a second class city in the [[Kusilvak Census Area, Alaska|Kusilvak Census Area]] of the [[Unorganized Borough, Alaska|Unorganized Borough]] in the western part of the U.S. state of [[Alaska]]. As of the [[United States Census, 2010|2010 census]], the population of the city was 677, up from 652 in 2000.\n\n==Location and Climate==\nAlakanuk is located at 62.688890\u00b0 North, 164.61528\u00b0 West (Sec. 14, T030N, R082W, Seward Meridian).<ref name=\"GR1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/geographies/reference-files/time-series/geo/gazetteer-files.html|publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]]|accessdate=2011-04-23|date=2011-02-12|title=US Gazetteer files: 2010, 2000, and 1990}}</ref> Alakanuk is located in the Bethel [[Recording District (Alaska)|Recording District]].\n\nAlakanuk is located at the east entrance of Alakanuk Pass, the major southern channel of the [[Yukon River]], {{convert|15|mi|km}} from the Bering Sea. It is part of the Yukon Delta National Wildlife Refuge. It lies {{convert|8|mi|km}} southwest of Emmonak, approximately {{convert|162|mi|km}} northwest of Bethel. It is the longest village on the lower Yukon - the development stretches over a {{convert|3|mi|km|adj=on}} area along the Pass. Approximately 25 homes along the bank are being threatened by erosion.\n\nThe climate of Alakanuk is subarctic, averaging {{convert|60|in|mm}} of snowfall and {{convert|19|in|mm}} of total precipitation per year. Temperatures range from between {{convert|-25|to|79|\u00b0F|\u00b0C}}. Heavy winds are frequent during the fall and winter. The Yukon River is used as an ice road during freeze-up, from November through May.\n\nAccording to the [[United States Census Bureau]], the city has a total area of {{convert|41.0|sqmi|km2}}, of which, {{convert|32.4|sqmi|km2}} of it is land and {{convert|8.7|sqmi|km2}} of it (21.14%) is water.\n\n==History and culture==\nAlakanuk is a Yup'ik word meaning \"wrong way\" or \"mistake village\", aptly applied to a village on this maze of watercourses. The village was first reported by G.R. Putnam of the U.S. Coast & Geodetic Survey in 1899. It was originally settled by a Yup'ik shaman named Anguksuar and his family. A Catholic mission school was built near the village. A post office was established in 1946. In 1948, the school was relocated to St. Mary's, and many families moved from the old school site to Alakanuk. It incorporated as a second-class city in 1969.\n\nA federally recognized tribe is located in the community\u2014the Village of Alakanuk.\n\n==Demographics==\n{{US Census population|align=left\n|1940= 61\n|1950= 140\n|1960= 278\n|1970= 414\n|1980= 522\n|1990= 544\n|2000= 652\n|2010= 677\n|estyear=2018\n|estimate=773\n|estref=<ref name=\"USCensusEst2018\">{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/programs-surveys/popest/data/tables.2018.html|title=Population and Housing Unit Estimates|accessdate=June 4, 2019}}</ref>\n|footnote=U.S. Decennial Census<ref name=\"DecennialCensus\">{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/programs-surveys/decennial-census.html|title=Census of Population and Housing|publisher=Census.gov|accessdate=June 4, 2015}}</ref>\n}}\nAlakanuk first appeared on the 1940 U.S. Census as the unincorporated native village of \"Alaganuck.\"<ref>https://www2.census.gov/prod2/decennial/documents/33973538v1ch11.pdf</ref> It returned as Alakanuk in 1950<ref>https://www2.census.gov/prod2/decennial/documents/41601749v2p51-54ch2.pdf</ref> and every successive census to date (2010)<ref>https://www.census.gov/prod/cen2010/cph-1-3.pdf</ref>. It formally incorporated in 1969.\n\nAs of the census<ref name=\"GR2\">{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov |publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]] |accessdate=2008-01-31 |title=U.S. Census website }}</ref> of 2000, there were 652 people, 139 households, and 118 families residing in the city.  The population density was 20.2 people per square mile (7.8/km\u00b2).  There were 160 housing units at an average density of 4.9 per square&nbsp;mile (1.9/km\u00b2).  The racial makeup of the city was 1.99% [[Race (United States Census)|White]], 95.40% [[Race (United States Census)|Native American]], 0.15% [[Race (United States Census)|Asian]], and 2.45% from two or more races.\n\nThere were 139 households out of which 59.7% had children under the age of 18 living with them, 57.6% were married couples living together, 12.9% had a female householder with no husband present, and 15.1% were non-families. 10.8% of all households were made up of individuals and 2.9% had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older.  The average household size was 4.69 and the average family size was 5.19.\n\nIn the city, the age distribution of the population shows 44.6% under the age of 18, 12.9% from 18 to 24, 21.9% from 25 to 44, 13.7% from 45 to 64, and 6.9% who were 65 years of age or older.  The median age was 20 years. For every 100 females, there were 111.0 males.  For every 100 females age 18 and over, there were 109.9 males.\n\nThe median income for a household in the city was $26,346, and the median income for a family was $26,500. Males had a median income of $19,792 versus $32,500 for females. The [[per capita income]] for the city was $6,884.  About 32.5% of families and 33.8% of the population were below the [[poverty line]], including 34.1% of those under age 18 and 25.8% of those age 65 or over.\n\n==Facilities, Utilities, and Health Care==\nThe City operates the water and piped sewer system and the central watering point. Approximately 90% of homes are connected. There is a sewage lagoon available for individuals to dump their [[Bucket toilet|honey bucket]]s. The City Council is the policy-making body for the utility. Water is derived from the Alakanuk Slough; it is treated, stored in a tank, and piped to most of the community. In 1998, 83 homes, the school and teachers' housing were connected to a new piped system. New facilities include a water treatment plant, heated 300,000-gal. water storage tank, vacuum sewage plant, sewage lagoon, Arctic piping, and household plumbing. A new subdivision is currently underway, and nine homes will be connected to the piped utilities. The city has funding from DEC for service connections to 20 homes. Ten homes have been moved from the erosion zone on the river bank and are ready for service. The city is planning to move an additional 10 homes. AVCP is building a 9-home subdivision, including water and sewer mains and service connections, for occupancy in 2002. The city completed a feasibility study for service area 7, which is the area across the river, and would like to obtain funding to make this expansion. The landfill is reported as inactive. Electricity is provided by AVEC. Local hospitals or health clinics include Alakanuk Health Clinic and Pearl E. Johnson Sub-Regional Clinic in Emmonak.  Alakanuk Health Clinic is a Primary Health Care facility. Alakanuk is classified as an isolated village, located in EMS Region 7A in the Yukon/Kuskokwim Region. Emergency Services have coastal and air access. Emergency service is provided by a health aide\n\n==Education==\nK-12 students attend Alakanuk School, operated by the [[Lower Yukon School District]].\n\n==Economy and Transportation==\nAlakanuk experiences a seasonal economy. 76 residents hold commercial fishing permits. Many have gill net permits, and set net fishermen sell their salmon to Seattle fish buyers. Poor fish returns since 1998 have significantly affected the community. Government employment and retail businesses provide limited year-round employment. Salmon, beluga whale, seal, moose and rabbit provide food sources. Some residents trap. Many residents travel to Emmonak to shop and attend social events and basketball tournaments.\n\n[[Alakanuk Airport]], a State-owned 2,200' long by 55' wide gravel airstrip, is available. An airport relocation project is underway, due to erosion. Grant Aviation, Hageland Aviation and Tanana Air Service offer passenger flight service. Alakanuk is easily accessible from the Yukon River and Bering Sea by barge and riverboat. Most passengers and mail arrive by air. There are no roads connecting Alakanuk with other population centers in the region, but ice roads are used in winter. Snowmachines and boats are used for local travel.\n\nTaxes:\tSales: 4%, Property: None, Special: None\n\n==Notable people==\n* [[Segundo Llorente|Father Segundo Llorente]], a [[Society of Jesus|Jesuit priest]] born in [[Spain]], was elected to the [[Alaska House of Representatives]] in 1960 as a [[write-in candidate]] while stationed in Alakanuk.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Portal|Alaska}}\n* [https://www.commerce.alaska.gov/dcra/DCRAExternal/community/Details/ce7e59f5-2ed0-4555-8468-0a18a3a36191 Alakanuk] at the Community Database Online from the [[Alaska Department of Commerce, Community and Economic Development|Alaska Division of Community and Regional Affairs]]\n* Maps from the [[Alaska Department of Labor and Workforce Development]]: [https://web.archive.org/web/20160304194705/http://labor.alaska.gov/research/alari/images/maps/6_26_6map.pdf 2000], [https://web.archive.org/web/20151222120351/http://labor.alaska.gov/research/census/placemaps/01200.pdf 2010]\n\n{{Kusilvak Census Area, Alaska}}\n{{Authority control}}\n[[Category:Cities in Alaska]]\n[[Category:Cities in Kusilvak Census Area, Alaska]]\n[[Category:Cities in Unorganized Borough, Alaska]]\n[[Category:Road-inaccessible communities of Alaska]]\n[[Category:Yukon River]]\n", "name_user": "Menchi", "label": "safe", "comment": "langtags", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Alakanuk,_Alaska"}
{"title_page": "Akiak, Alaska", "text_new": "{{distinguish|Aniak, Alaska}}\n{{Infobox settlement\n| official_name                   = Akiak\n| native_name                     = Akiaq\n     | native_name_lang        = esu\n| settlement_type                 = [[City (Alaska)|City]]\n| nickname                        = \n| motto                           = <!-- Images -->\n| image_skyline                   = AKI-b.jpg\n| imagesize                       = \n| image_caption                   = Aerial view of Akiak, 1996\n| image_flag                      = \n| image_seal                      = <!-- Maps -->\n| pushpin_map                     = Alaska\n| pushpin_map_caption             = Location in Alaska\n\n<!-- Location -->| subdivision_type                = Country\n| subdivision_name                = United States\n| subdivision_type1               = [[U.S. state|State]]\n| subdivision_name1               = [[Alaska]]\n| subdivision_type2               = [[List of boroughs and census areas in Alaska|Census Area]]\n| subdivision_name2               = [[Bethel Census Area, Alaska|Bethel]]\n| government_footnotes            = \n| government_type                 = \n| leader_title                    = [[Mayor]]\n| leader_name                     = Debra M. Jackson\n| leader_title1                   = [[Alaska Senate|State senator]]\n| leader_name1                    = [[Lyman Hoffman]] ([[Democratic Party (United States)|D-C]])<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.alaskasenate.org/2020/member/lyman-hoffman/ |title=Senator Lyman Hoffman |publisher=Alaskasenate.org |website=Alaska Senate Majority |access-date=November 16, 2019}}</ref>\n| leader_title2                   = [[Alaska House of Representatives|State rep.]]\n| leader_name2                    = [[Tiffany Zulkosky]] ([[Democratic Party (United States)|D]])\n| established_title               = [[Municipal corporation|Incorporated]]\n| established_date                = July 9, 1970<ref>{{cite journal|title=Directory of Borough and City Officials 1974|journal=Alaska Local Government|volume=XIII|issue=2|page=12|location=Juneau|publisher=[[Alaska Department of Commerce, Community and Economic Development|Alaska Department of Community and Regional Affairs]]|date=January 1974}}</ref>\n\n<!-- Area -->| area_magnitude                  = \n| area_footnotes                  = <ref name=\"CenPopGazetteer2016\">{{cite web|title=2018 U.S. Gazetteer Files|url=https://www2.census.gov/geo/docs/maps-data/data/gazetteer/2018_Gazetteer/2018_gaz_place_02.txt|publisher=United States Census Bureau|accessdate=Jul 1, 2019}}</ref>\n| area_total_km2                  = 7.77\n| area_land_km2                   = 4.89\n| area_water_km2                  = 2.88\n| area_total_sq_mi                = 3.00\n| area_land_sq_mi                 = 1.89\n| area_water_sq_mi                = 1.11\n<!-- Population -->| population_as_of                = [[2010 United States Census|2010]]\n| population_footnotes            = \n| population_total                = 346\n| population_density_km2          = 80.57\n\n<!-- General information -->| timezone                        = [[Alaska Time Zone|Alaska (AKST)]]\n| utc_offset                      = -9\n| timezone_DST                    = AKDT\n| utc_offset_DST                  = -8\n| elevation_footnotes             = \n| elevation_m                     = 4\n| elevation_ft                    = 13\n| coordinates                     = {{coord|60|54|36|N|161|13|6|W|region:US-AK|display=inline}}\n| postal_code_type                = [[ZIP code]]\n| postal_code                     = 99552\n| area_code                       = [[Area code 907|907]]\n| area_code_type                  = [[North American Numbering Plan|Area code]]\n| blank_name                      = [[Federal Information Processing Standard|FIPS code]]\n| blank_info                      = 02-00870\n| blank1_name                     = [[Geographic Names Information System|GNIS]] feature ID\n| blank1_info                     = {{GNIS 4|1398012}}\n| website                         = {{URL|https://www.commerce.alaska.gov/dcra/DCRAExternal/community/Details/f35f3e25-97e9-423d-8a37-f06d15b4edbf}}\n| footnotes                       = \n| pop_est_as_of                   = 2018\n| pop_est_footnotes               = <ref name=\"USCensusEst2018\"/>\n| population_est                  = 394\n| population_density_sq_mi        = 208.69\n| unit_pref                       = Imperial\n| name                            = \n}}\n'''Akiak''' {{small|(ACK-ee-ack)}} ({{lang-esu|Akiaq}}) is a city in [[Bethel Census Area, Alaska|Bethel Census Area]], [[Alaska]], United States. The population was 346 at the [[2010 United States Census|2010 census]],<ref name=\"Census 2010\">{{cite web| url=http://factfinder.census.gov/bkmk/table/1.0/en/DEC/10_DP/G001/1600000US0200870| archive-url=https://archive.today/20200212175705/http://factfinder.census.gov/bkmk/table/1.0/en/DEC/10_DP/G001/1600000US0200870| url-status=dead| archive-date=February 12, 2020| title=Geographic Identifiers: 2010 Demographic Profile Data (G001): Akiak city, Alaska| publisher=U.S. Census Bureau, American Factfinder| accessdate=September 18, 2013}}</ref> up from 309 in 2000.\n\n==Geography and climate==\nAkiak is located at {{Coord|60|54|36|N|161|13|6|W|type:city}} (60.912220, -161.21389)<ref name=\"GR1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/geographies/reference-files/time-series/geo/gazetteer-files.html|publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]]|accessdate=2011-04-23|date=2011-02-12|title=US Gazetteer files: 2010, 2000, and 1990}}</ref> (Sec. 32, T010N, R067W, Seward Meridian), on the west bank of the [[Kuskokwim River]], {{convert|42|mi}} northeast of [[Bethel, Alaska|Bethel]], on the [[Yukon\u2013Kuskokwim Delta]]. Akiak is located in the Bethel [[Recording District (Alaska)|Recording District]].\n\nAccording to the [[U.S. Census Bureau]], the city has a total area of {{convert|8.1|sqkm|disp=flip}}, of which {{convert|5.4|sqkm|disp=flip}} is land and {{convert|2.6|sqkm|disp=flip}}, or 32.58%, is water. Precipitation averages {{convert|16|in}} in this area, with snowfall of {{convert|50|in}}. Summer temperatures range from {{convert|42|F}} to {{convert|62|F}}. Winter temperatures range from {{convert|-2|F}} to {{convert|19|F}}.\n\n==History and culture==\nIn 1880, the village, then known as '''Akkiagamute''', had a population of 175. The current name ''Akiak'' means \"the other side,\" since this place was a crossing to the [[Yukon River]] basin during the winter for area [[Yupiit]]. The community established a post office in 1916. A [[U.S. Public Health Service]] built a hospital in the 1920s. The city was incorporated in 1970.\n\nA [[Federally recognized tribe|federally recognized]] [[Alaska Native tribe]], the [[Akiak Native Community]] is located in the Akiak. Akiak is a Yup'ik village with a reliance on subsistence and fishing activities.\n\n==Demographics==\n{{US Census population|align=left\n|1880= 175\n|1890= 97\n|1920= 150\n|1930= 228\n|1940= 209\n|1950= 168\n|1960= 187\n|1970= 171\n|1980= 198\n|1990= 285\n|2000= 309\n|2010= 346\n|estyear=2018\n|estimate=394\n|estref=<ref name=\"USCensusEst2018\">{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/programs-surveys/popest/data/tables.2018.html|title=Population and Housing Unit Estimates|accessdate=June 4, 2019}}</ref>\n|footnote=U.S. Decennial Census<ref name=\"DecennialCensus\">{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/programs-surveys/decennial-census.html|title=Census of Population and Housing|publisher=Census.gov|accessdate=June 4, 2015}}</ref>\n}}\nAkiak first appeared on the 1880 U.S. Census as the unincorporated [[Alaska Native]] (Inuit) village of \"Akkiagamute.\" All 175 residents were Inuit.<ref>[http://www2.census.gov/prod2/decennial/documents/1880a_v1-17.pdf \"Areas, Dwellings, and Families.\"] US Census Bureau.</ref> In 1890, it returned as \"Akiagamiut\" with 97 residents (all Alaska Native).<ref>{{cite web |last1=Porter |first1=Robert B. |title=Population and Resources of Alaska at the Eleventh Census: 1890 |url=http://www2.census.gov/prod2/decennial/documents/1890a_v8-01.pdf |website=US Bureau of the Census Library |publisher=Government Printing Office |location=Washington, DC |date=1893}}</ref> It did not appear on the census again until 1920, then as Akiak.<ref>https://www2.census.gov/prod2/decennial/documents/41084484v1ch5.pdf</ref> It has returned in every successive census. It formally incorporated in 1970.\n\nAs of the census<ref name=\"GR2\">{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov |publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]] |accessdate=2008-01-31 |title=U.S. Census website }}</ref> of 2000, there were 309 people, 69 households, and 54 families residing in the city. The population density was 157.2 people per square mile (60.6/km\u00b2). There were 76 housing units at an average density of 38.7 per square&nbsp;mile (14.9/km\u00b2). The racial makeup of the city was 4.85% [[Race (United States Census)|White]], 92.88% [[Race (United States Census)|Native American]], and 2.27% from two or more races. 0.65% of the population were [[Race (United States Census)|Hispanic]] or [[Race (United States Census)|Latino]] of any race.\n\nOf Akiak's 69 households, 53.6% had children under the age of 18 living with them, 43.5% were married couples living together, 20.3% had a female householder with no husband present, and 21.7% were non-families. 18.8% of all households were made up of individuals and 4.3% had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older. The average household size was 4.48 and the average family size was 5.24.\n\nIn the city, the age distribution of the population shows 43.4% under the age of 18, 11.3% from 18 to 24, 23.9% from 25 to 44, 14.6% from 45 to 64, and 6.8% who were 65 years of age or older. The median age was 21 years. For every 100 females, there were 122.3 males. For every 100 females age 18 and over, there were 105.9 males.\n\nThe median income for a household in the city was $26,250, and the median income for a family was $36,875. Males had a median income of $21,875 versus $11,667 for females. The [[per capita income]] for the city was $8,326. About 25.0% of families and 33.9% of the population were below the [[poverty line]], including 40.3% of those under the age of eighteen and 6.7% of those sixty five or over.\n\n==Public services==\n{{Unreferenced section|date=September 2008}}\n\nA new well-water treatment plant and storage tank were recently completed. The school and clinic are connected directly to the water plant. Individual wells, septic systems and plumbing were installed in 14 HUD homes during 1997. Sewage disposal is currently by [[septic tank]]s, [[Bucket toilet|honey bucket]]s or [[outhouse|privies]], but major improvements are underway. A piped water and [[gravity sewer]] system is under construction, with household plumbing. 67 homes need water and sewer service. Most residents are dependent upon the washeteria for laundry and bathing. The city provides septic pumping services. Electricity is provided by the city of Akiak. There is one school located in the community, attended by 99 students.\n\nThe city is currently home to the world's third largest museum of [[taxidermy]]. Local hospitals or health clinics include Edith Kawagley Memorial Clinic (907-765-7125). Edith Kawagley Memorial Clinic is a Primary Health Care facility. Akiak is classified as an isolated village; it is found in EMS Region 7A in the Yukon/Kuskokwim Region. Emergency services have river and air access and are provided by a health aide.\n\n==Economy and transportation==\n{{Unreferenced section|date=September 2008}}\n\nThe majority of the year-round employment in Akiak is with the city, schools or other public services. Commercial fishing or [[Bureau of Land Management|BLM]] fire-fighting also provide seasonal income. Twenty-seven residents hold commercial fishing permits. The community is interested in developing a fish processing plant and tourism. Subsistence activities are important to residents. Poor fish returns since 1997 have significantly affected the community.\n\nThe airport has a gravel runway in good condition, measuring {{convert|3196|ft}} long by {{convert|75|ft}} wide, at an elevation of {{convert|30|ft}}. The strip provides chartered or private air access year-round. [[Arctic Circle Air Service]], [[Grant Aviation]], and [[Hageland Aviation]] offer passenger flight service. Snow machines, ATVs, and skiffs are used extensively for local transportation to nearby villages. There are no docking facilities.\n\nThe town has no sales tax, property tax, or special taxes.  The sale or importation of [[alcoholic beverage|alcohol]] is banned in the village.\n\n== Notable people ==\n\n* [[Nora Guinn]], judge\n* [[Carl Smith (activist)|Carl Smith]], teenage activist who took part in the [[school strike for climate]].\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Portal|Alaska}}\n* [https://www.commerce.alaska.gov/dcra/DCRAExternal/community/Details/f35f3e25-97e9-423d-8a37-f06d15b4edbf Akiak] at the Community Database Online from the [[Alaska Department of Commerce, Community and Economic Development|Alaska Division of Community and Regional Affairs]]\n* Maps from the [[Alaska Department of Labor and Workforce Development]]: [https://web.archive.org/web/20160123193314/http://labor.alaska.gov/research/alari/images/maps/6_4_4map.pdf 2000], [https://web.archive.org/web/20151222122100/http://labor.alaska.gov/research/census/placemaps/00870.pdf 2010]\n\n{{Coord|display=title|60.912220|-161.21389}}\n{{Bethel Census Area, Alaska}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Akiak, Alaska| ]]\n[[Category:Cities in Bethel Census Area, Alaska]]\n[[Category:Cities in Alaska]]\n[[Category:Road-inaccessible communities of Alaska]]\n[[Category:Cities in Unorganized Borough, Alaska]]\n", "text_old": "{{distinguish|Aniak, Alaska}}\n{{Infobox settlement\n| official_name                   = Akiak\n| native_name             