Community and Regional Affairs]]|date=January 1974}}</ref>\n\n<!-- Area -->| area_magnitude                  = \n| area_footnotes                  = <ref name=\"CenPopGazetteer2016\">{{cite web|title=2018 U.S. Gazetteer Files|url=https://www2.census.gov/geo/docs/maps-data/data/gazetteer/2018_Gazetteer/2018_gaz_place_02.txt|publisher=United States Census Bureau|accessdate=Jul 1, 2019}}</ref>\n| area_total_km2                  = 7.77\n| area_land_km2                   = 4.89\n| area_water_km2                  = 2.88\n| area_total_sq_mi                = 3.00\n| area_land_sq_mi                 = 1.89\n| area_water_sq_mi                = 1.11\n<!-- Population -->| population_as_of                = [[2010 United States Census|2010]]\n| population_footnotes            = \n| population_total                = 346\n| population_density_km2          = 80.57\n\n<!-- General information -->| timezone                        = [[Alaska Time Zone|Alaska (AKST)]]\n| utc_offset                      = -9\n| timezone_DST                    = AKDT\n| utc_offset_DST                  = -8\n| elevation_footnotes             = \n| elevation_m                     = 4\n| elevation_ft                    = 13\n| coordinates                     = {{coord|60|54|36|N|161|13|6|W|region:US-AK|display=inline}}\n| postal_code_type                = [[ZIP code]]\n| postal_code                     = 99552\n| area_code                       = [[Area code 907|907]]\n| area_code_type                  = [[North American Numbering Plan|Area code]]\n| blank_name                      = [[Federal Information Processing Standard|FIPS code]]\n| blank_info                      = 02-00870\n| blank1_name                     = [[Geographic Names Information System|GNIS]] feature ID\n| blank1_info                     = {{GNIS 4|1398012}}\n| website                         = {{URL|https://www.commerce.alaska.gov/dcra/DCRAExternal/community/Details/f35f3e25-97e9-423d-8a37-f06d15b4edbf}}\n| footnotes                       = \n| pop_est_as_of                   = 2018\n| pop_est_footnotes               = <ref name=\"USCensusEst2018\"/>\n| population_est                  = 394\n| population_density_sq_mi        = 208.69\n| unit_pref                       = Imperial\n| name                            = \n}}\n'''Akiak''' (ACK-ee-ack) ('''Akiaq''' in [[Yupik language|Central Yup'ik]]) is a city in [[Bethel Census Area, Alaska|Bethel Census Area]], [[Alaska]], United States. The population was 346 at the [[2010 United States Census|2010 census]],<ref name=\"Census 2010\">{{cite web| url=http://factfinder.census.gov/bkmk/table/1.0/en/DEC/10_DP/G001/1600000US0200870| archive-url=https://archive.today/20200212175705/http://factfinder.census.gov/bkmk/table/1.0/en/DEC/10_DP/G001/1600000US0200870| url-status=dead| archive-date=February 12, 2020| title=Geographic Identifiers: 2010 Demographic Profile Data (G001): Akiak city, Alaska| publisher=U.S. Census Bureau, American Factfinder| accessdate=September 18, 2013}}</ref> up from 309 in 2000.\n\n==Geography and climate==\nAkiak is located at {{Coord|60|54|36|N|161|13|6|W|type:city}} (60.912220, -161.21389)<ref name=\"GR1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/geographies/reference-files/time-series/geo/gazetteer-files.html|publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]]|accessdate=2011-04-23|date=2011-02-12|title=US Gazetteer files: 2010, 2000, and 1990}}</ref> (Sec. 32, T010N, R067W, Seward Meridian), on the west bank of the [[Kuskokwim River]], {{convert|42|mi}} northeast of [[Bethel, Alaska|Bethel]], on the [[Yukon\u2013Kuskokwim Delta]]. Akiak is located in the Bethel [[Recording District (Alaska)|Recording District]].\n\nAccording to the [[U.S. Census Bureau]], the city has a total area of {{convert|8.1|sqkm|disp=flip}}, of which {{convert|5.4|sqkm|disp=flip}} is land and {{convert|2.6|sqkm|disp=flip}}, or 32.58%, is water. Precipitation averages {{convert|16|in}} in this area, with snowfall of {{convert|50|in}}. Summer temperatures range from {{convert|42|F}} to {{convert|62|F}}. Winter temperatures range from {{convert|-2|F}} to {{convert|19|F}}.\n\n==History and culture==\nIn 1880, the village, then known as '''Akkiagamute''', had a population of 175. The current name ''Akiak'' means \"the other side,\" since this place was a crossing to the [[Yukon River]] basin during the winter for area [[Yupiit]]. The community established a post office in 1916. A [[U.S. Public Health Service]] built a hospital in the 1920s. The city was incorporated in 1970.\n\nA [[Federally recognized tribe|federally recognized]] [[Alaska Native tribe]], the [[Akiak Native Community]] is located in the Akiak. Akiak is a Yup'ik village with a reliance on subsistence and fishing activities.\n\n==Demographics==\n{{US Census population|align=left\n|1880= 175\n|1890= 97\n|1920= 150\n|1930= 228\n|1940= 209\n|1950= 168\n|1960= 187\n|1970= 171\n|1980= 198\n|1990= 285\n|2000= 309\n|2010= 346\n|estyear=2018\n|estimate=394\n|estref=<ref name=\"USCensusEst2018\">{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/programs-surveys/popest/data/tables.2018.html|title=Population and Housing Unit Estimates|accessdate=June 4, 2019}}</ref>\n|footnote=U.S. Decennial Census<ref name=\"DecennialCensus\">{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/programs-surveys/decennial-census.html|title=Census of Population and Housing|publisher=Census.gov|accessdate=June 4, 2015}}</ref>\n}}\nAkiak first appeared on the 1880 U.S. Census as the unincorporated [[Alaska Native]] (Inuit) village of \"Akkiagamute.\" All 175 residents were Inuit.<ref>[http://www2.census.gov/prod2/decennial/documents/1880a_v1-17.pdf \"Areas, Dwellings, and Families.\"] US Census Bureau.</ref> In 1890, it returned as \"Akiagamiut\" with 97 residents (all Alaska Native).<ref>{{cite web |last1=Porter |first1=Robert B. |title=Population and Resources of Alaska at the Eleventh Census: 1890 |url=http://www2.census.gov/prod2/decennial/documents/1890a_v8-01.pdf |website=US Bureau of the Census Library |publisher=Government Printing Office |location=Washington, DC |date=1893}}</ref> It did not appear on the census again until 1920, then as Akiak.<ref>https://www2.census.gov/prod2/decennial/documents/41084484v1ch5.pdf</ref> It has returned in every successive census. It formally incorporated in 1970.\n\nAs of the census<ref name=\"GR2\">{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov |publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]] |accessdate=2008-01-31 |title=U.S. Census website }}</ref> of 2000, there were 309 people, 69 households, and 54 families residing in the city. The population density was 157.2 people per square mile (60.6/km\u00b2). There were 76 housing units at an average density of 38.7 per square&nbsp;mile (14.9/km\u00b2). The racial makeup of the city was 4.85% [[Race (United States Census)|White]], 92.88% [[Race (United States Census)|Native American]], and 2.27% from two or more races. 0.65% of the population were [[Race (United States Census)|Hispanic]] or [[Race (United States Census)|Latino]] of any race.\n\nOf Akiak's 69 households, 53.6% had children under the age of 18 living with them, 43.5% were married couples living together, 20.3% had a female householder with no husband present, and 21.7% were non-families. 18.8% of all households were made up of individuals and 4.3% had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older. The average household size was 4.48 and the average family size was 5.24.\n\nIn the city, the age distribution of the population shows 43.4% under the age of 18, 11.3% from 18 to 24, 23.9% from 25 to 44, 14.6% from 45 to 64, and 6.8% who were 65 years of age or older. The median age was 21 years. For every 100 females, there were 122.3 males. For every 100 females age 18 and over, there were 105.9 males.\n\nThe median income for a household in the city was $26,250, and the median income for a family was $36,875. Males had a median income of $21,875 versus $11,667 for females. The [[per capita income]] for the city was $8,326. About 25.0% of families and 33.9% of the population were below the [[poverty line]], including 40.3% of those under the age of eighteen and 6.7% of those sixty five or over.\n\n==Public services==\n{{Unreferenced section|date=September 2008}}\n\nA new well-water treatment plant and storage tank were recently completed. The school and clinic are connected directly to the water plant. Individual wells, septic systems and plumbing were installed in 14 HUD homes during 1997. Sewage disposal is currently by [[septic tank]]s, [[Bucket toilet|honey bucket]]s or [[outhouse|privies]], but major improvements are underway. A piped water and [[gravity sewer]] system is under construction, with household plumbing. 67 homes need water and sewer service. Most residents are dependent upon the washeteria for laundry and bathing. The city provides septic pumping services. Electricity is provided by the city of Akiak. There is one school located in the community, attended by 99 students.\n\nThe city is currently home to the world's third largest museum of [[taxidermy]]. Local hospitals or health clinics include Edith Kawagley Memorial Clinic (907-765-7125). Edith Kawagley Memorial Clinic is a Primary Health Care facility. Akiak is classified as an isolated village; it is found in EMS Region 7A in the Yukon/Kuskokwim Region. Emergency services have river and air access and are provided by a health aide.\n\n==Economy and transportation==\n{{Unreferenced section|date=September 2008}}\n\nThe majority of the year-round employment in Akiak is with the city, schools or other public services. Commercial fishing or [[Bureau of Land Management|BLM]] fire-fighting also provide seasonal income. Twenty-seven residents hold commercial fishing permits. The community is interested in developing a fish processing plant and tourism. Subsistence activities are important to residents. Poor fish returns since 1997 have significantly affected the community.\n\nThe airport has a gravel runway in good condition, measuring {{convert|3196|ft}} long by {{convert|75|ft}} wide, at an elevation of {{convert|30|ft}}. The strip provides chartered or private air access year-round. [[Arctic Circle Air Service]], [[Grant Aviation]], and [[Hageland Aviation]] offer passenger flight service. Snow machines, ATVs, and skiffs are used extensively for local transportation to nearby villages. There are no docking facilities.\n\nThe town has no sales tax, property tax, or special taxes.  The sale or importation of [[alcoholic beverage|alcohol]] is banned in the village.\n\n== Notable people ==\n\n* [[Nora Guinn]], judge\n* [[Carl Smith (activist)|Carl Smith]], teenage activist who took part in the [[school strike for climate]].\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Portal|Alaska}}\n* [https://www.commerce.alaska.gov/dcra/DCRAExternal/community/Details/f35f3e25-97e9-423d-8a37-f06d15b4edbf Akiak] at the Community Database Online from the [[Alaska Department of Commerce, Community and Economic Development|Alaska Division of Community and Regional Affairs]]\n* Maps from the [[Alaska Department of Labor and Workforce Development]]: [https://web.archive.org/web/20160123193314/http://labor.alaska.gov/research/alari/images/maps/6_4_4map.pdf 2000], [https://web.archive.org/web/20151222122100/http://labor.alaska.gov/research/census/placemaps/00870.pdf 2010]\n\n{{Coord|display=title|60.912220|-161.21389}}\n{{Bethel Census Area, Alaska}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Akiak, Alaska| ]]\n[[Category:Cities in Bethel Census Area, Alaska]]\n[[Category:Cities in Alaska]]\n[[Category:Road-inaccessible communities of Alaska]]\n[[Category:Cities in Unorganized Borough, Alaska]]\n", "name_user": "Menchi", "label": "safe", "comment": "langtags", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Akiak,_Alaska"}
{"title_page": "First Hungarian Republic", "text_new": "{{Distinguish|text=the [[Hungarian People's Republic|Hungarian People's Republic of 1949\u20131989]]}}\n{{Use American English|date=March 2019}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2019}}\n{{Infobox country\n |conventional_long_name = Hungarian Republic\n |native_name          = {{native name|hu|Magyar K\u00f6zt\u00e1rsas\u00e1g|paren=omit}}\n |common_name          = Hungary\n |life_span            = 1918\u20131919\n |image_flag           = Flag of Hungary (1918-1919).svg\n |flag                 = Flag of Hungary\n |flag_type            = Flag\n |image_coat           = Coat of arms of Hungary (1918-1919).svg\n |coa_size             = 50\n |symbol               = Coat of arms of Hungary\n |symbol_type          = Coat of arms\n |national_anthem      = \"[[Himnusz]]\"\n |image_map            = Partition of Austria-Hungary 1919 map.jpg\n |image_map_caption    = [[Aftermath of World War I#Austria-Hungary|Partition of Austria-Hungary]]: {{nowr|boundaries as defined in the treaties, 1919}}\n |status               = [[List of states with limited recognition|It became an Unrecognized]] {{nowr|[[rump state]]}}\n |capital              = [[Budapest]]\n |coordinates          = {{coord|47|29|N|19|02|E|source:eswiki_type:country|display=title}}\n |languages_type       = Official&nbsp;language\n |languages            = [[Hungarian language|Hungarian]]\n |languages2_sub       = yes\n |languages2_type      = Common&nbsp;languages\n |languages2           = [[German language|German]], [[Slovak language|Slovak]], [[Croatian language|Croatian]], [[Romanian language|Romanian]]\n |government_type      = [[People's republic]]\n |title_leader         = [[Regent of Hungary|Regent]]\n |year_leader1         = 7 August 1919\n |leader1              = [[Archduke Joseph August of Austria|Joseph August]]\n |title_representative = [[List of heads of state of Hungary|President]]\n |representative1      = [[Mih\u00e1ly K\u00e1rolyi]]\n |representative2      = [[Gyula Peidl]]&nbsp;(acting)\n |year_representative1 = {{nowr|16 November 1918}}  \n |year_representative2 = 1 August 1919  \n |title_deputy         = [[List of Prime Ministers of Hungary|Prime Minister]]\n |deputy1              = [[Mih\u00e1ly K\u00e1rolyi]]\n |deputy2              = [[D\u00e9nes Berinkey]]\n |deputy3              = [[Gyula Peidl]]\n |deputy4              = [[Istv\u00e1n Friedrich]]\n |year_deputy1         = 31 October 1918\n |year_deputy2         = 11 January 1919\n |year_deputy3         = 1 August 1919\n |year_deputy4         = 7 August 1919\n |legislature          = [[Hungarian National Council|National Council]]\n |era                  = Interwar period\n |event_pre            = [[Aster Revolution]]\n |event_start          = Establishment\n |event1               = [[Hungarian Soviet Republic|Soviet overthrow]]\n |event2               = Re-establishment\n |event_end            = Dissolution\n |event_post           = [[Treaty of Trianon]]\n |date_pre             = 31 October 1918\n |date_start           = 16 November 1918\n |date_event1          = 21 March 1919\n |date_event2          = 1 August 1919\n |date_end             = 8 August 1919\n |date_post            = 4 June 1920\n |area_km2             = 282,870\n |area_sq_mi           = 109,220\n |area_footnote        = {{efn|name=fn1}}\n |stat_year1           = 1920\n |stat_pop1            = 7,980,143\n |currency             = {{ubl|style=text-indent:-1em;margin-left:1em;|[[Austro-Hungarian korona]] (until 1919)|[[Hungarian korona]]}}\n |p1                   = Kingdom of Hungary (1867\u20131918){{!}}Kingdom of&nbsp;Hungary\n |p2                   = Hungarian Soviet Republic{{!}}Soviet Hungary\n |flag_p1              = Flag of Hungary (1915-1918; angels).svg\n |flag_p2              = Flag of Hungary (1919).svg\n |s1                   = Hungarian Republic (1919\u201320){{!}}Hungarian Republic\n |s2                   = Hungarian Soviet Republic{{!}}Soviet Hungary\n |flag_s1              = Flag of Hungary (1920\u20131946).svg\n |flag_s2              = Flag of Hungary (1919).svg\n |today                = [[Hungary]]\n |footnotes            = {{notelist|refs={{efn|name=fn1|In 1918. {{harv|Tarsoly|1995|pp=595\u2013597.}}}}}}\n}}\nThe '''First Hungarian Republic''' ({{lang-hu|Els\u0151 Magyar K\u00f6zt\u00e1rsas\u00e1g}}),<ref>{{cite web|last=Lambert|first=S.|title=The First Hungarian Republic|url=http://theorangefiles.hu/the-first-hungarian-republic/|work=The Orange Files|accessdate=2019-03-11|df=dmy-all}}</ref> until 21 March 1919 the '''Hungarian People's Republic''' ({{lang|hu|Magyar N\u00e9pk\u00f6zt\u00e1rsas\u00e1g}}), was a short-lived unrecognized [[people's republic]] that existed&nbsp;\u2013 apart from a {{nowr|133-day}} interruption in the form of the [[Hungarian Soviet Republic]]&nbsp;\u2013 from 16 November 1918 until 8 August 1919. The republic was established in the wake of the [[Aftermath of World War I#Austria-Hungary|dissolution of Austria-Hungary]] following [[World War I]]. The First Hungarian Republic replaced the [[Kingdom of Hungary (Austria-Hungary)|Kingdom of Hungary]], and was in turn replaced by the [[Hungarian Republic (1919\u201320)|Hungarian Republic]], another short-lived state from 1919 to 1920. During the rule of Count [[Mih\u00e1ly K\u00e1rolyi]]'s pacifist cabinet, Hungary lost the control over approximately 75% of its former pre-World War I territories ({{convert|325411|km2|abbr=on}}) without armed resistance and was subject to foreign occupation. \n\nFollowing this period, the [[Allies of World War I|Allied Powers of World War I]] severely pressured the Hungarians into retreating behind post-war demarcation lines as a provision to the [[Paris Peace Conference, 1919|Paris Peace Conference of 1919]], their attempt to establish new [[nation state]]s among the former kingdom's non-Hungarian citizens&nbsp;\u2013 the principal beneficiaries of which were the [[Kingdom of Romania]], the [[Kingdom of Serbs, Croats, and Slovenes]], the [[First Austrian Republic|Austrian Republic]], and the [[First Czechoslovak Republic|Czechoslovak Republic]]. The subsequent [[Treaty of Trianon|Treaty of Peace between the Allied and Associated Powers and Hungary]] was signed under protest by the latter.\n\n== Name ==\n[[File:President Mihaly Karolyi's speech after the proclamation of the First Hungarian Republic on 16 november, 1918.webm|thumb|300px|left|President Mihaly Karolyi's speech after the proclamation of the First Hungarian Republic on 16 november, 1918(1080p video)]]\n[[File:Bela Linder&#039;s pacifist speech on 2 November 1918.webm|thumb|left|300px|B\u00e9la Linder&#039;s pacifist speech and declaration of self-disarmament on 2 November 1918]]\n\"Hungarian People's Republic\" was adopted as the official name of the country on 16 November 1918,<ref name=\"november16\">{{cite wikisource|1918. \u00e9vi n\u00e9phat\u00e1rozat||hu|noicon=y}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last1=P\u00f6l\u00f6skei|first1=F.|last2=Gergely|first2=J.|last3 =Izs\u00e1k|first3=L.|display-authors=1|date=1995|title=Magyarorsz\u00e1g t\u00f6rt\u00e9nete, 1918\u20131990|location=Budapest|publisher=Korona Kiad\u00f3|lang=hu|isbn=963-8153-55-5|page=17}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|title=Minisztertan\u00e1csi jegyz\u0151k\u00f6nyvek: 1918. november 16.|publisher=DigitArchiv|page=4|lang=hu}}</ref> and remained in use until the overthrow of the [[D\u00e9nes Berinkey]] government on 21 March 1919. Following the collapse of the [[Hungarian Soviet Republic]], the [[Gyula Peidl]] government restored the pre-communist name of the state on 2 August 1919.<ref name=\"august2\">{{cite wikisource|A Magyar N\u00e9pk\u00f6zt\u00e1rsas\u00e1g Korm\u00e1ny\u00e1nak 1. sz\u00e1mu rendelete Magyarorsz\u00e1g \u00e1llamform\u00e1ja t\u00e1rgy\u00e1ban||hu|noicon=y}}</ref><ref name=\"P\u00f6l\u00f6skei\">{{cite book|last1=P\u00f6l\u00f6skei|first1=F.|last2=Gergely|first2 =J.|last3=Izs\u00e1k|first3=L.|display-authors=1|date=1995|title=Magyarorsz\u00e1g t\u00f6rt\u00e9nete, 1918\u20131990|location=Budapest|publisher=Korona Kiad\u00f3|lang=hu|isbn=963-8153-55-5|pages=32\u201333}}</ref>\n\nThe government of [[Istv\u00e1n Friedrich]] changed the name to \"[[Hungarian Republic (1919\u201320)|Hungarian Republic]]\" on 8 August;<ref>{{cite wikisource|A Magyar K\u00f6zt\u00e1rsas\u00e1g minisztereln\u00f6k\u00e9nek 1. sz\u00e1mu rendelete a sajt\u00f3term\u00e9kekr\u0151l||hu|noicon=y}}</ref><ref>{{cite wikisource|4072/1919. M. E. sz\u00e1m\u00fa rendelet||hu|noicon=y}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last=Raffay|first=E.|date=1990|title=Trianon titkai, avagy hogyan b\u00e1ntak el orsz\u00e1gunkkal|lang=hu|location=Budapest|publisher=Tornado Damenia|page=125|isbn=963-02-7639-9}}</ref> however, the denomination \"Hungarian People's Republic\" appeared on some government-issued decrees during this period.<ref>{{cite wikisource|3923/1919. M. E. sz\u00e1m\u00fa rendelet||hu|noicon=y}}</ref><ref>{{cite wikisource|70762/1919. K. M. sz\u00e1m\u00fa rendelet||hu|noicon=y}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\n\n=== K\u00e1rolyi era ===\n{{History of Hungary}}\nThe Hungarian People's Republic was created by the [[Aster Revolution]], which started in [[Budapest]] on 31 October 1918. That day, King [[Charles I of Austria|Charles IV]] appointed the revolt's leader, [[Mih\u00e1ly K\u00e1rolyi]], as Hungarian prime minister. Almost his first act was to formally terminate the [[personal union]] between Austria and Hungary. On 13 November, Charles [[Charles I of Austria#Proclamations|issued a proclamation]] withdrawing from Hungarian politics. A few days later the provisional government proclaimed Hungary a people's republic,<ref name=\"november16\"/> with K\u00e1rolyi as both prime minister and interim president. This event ended 400 years of rule by the [[House of Habsburg]].\n\nThe K\u00e1rolyi government's measures failed to stem popular discontent, especially when the [[Entente powers]] began distributing slices of what many considered [[Greater Hungary (political concept)|Hungary's traditional territory]] to the majority ethnic groups in [[Kingdom of Romania]], the [[Kingdom of Yugoslavia|Kingdom of Serbs, Croats and Slovenes]], and the [[First Czechoslovak Republic]]. The new government and its supporters had pinned their hopes for maintaining Hungary's territorial integrity on the abandonment of [[Cisleithania]] and Germany, the securing of a separate peace, and exploiting K\u00e1rolyi's close connections in the [[French Third Republic]].\n\nThe Entente considered Hungary a partner in the defeated [[Dual Monarchy]], and dashed the Hungarians' hopes with the delivery of successive diplomatic notes. Each demanded the surrender of more land to other ethnic groups. On 20 March 1919, the French head of the Entente mission in Budapest gave K\u00e1rolyi a note<!--Vix note--> delineating the final postwar boundaries, which the Hungarians found unacceptable.<ref>{{cite book |last= Romsics|first= Ign\u00e1c|title= Magyarorsz\u00e1g t\u00f6rt\u00e9nete a XX. sz\u00e1zadban|year= 2004|publisher= Osiris Kiad\u00f3|location= Budapest|language= Hungarian|isbn= 963-389-590-1|page= 123}}</ref> K\u00e1rolyi and Prime Minister [[D\u00e9nes Berinkey]] were now in an impossible position. They knew accepting the French note would endanger the country's territorial integrity, but were in no position to reject it. In protest, Berinkey resigned.\n\nK\u00e1rolyi informed the cabinet that only the [[Hungarian Social Democratic Party]] could possibly form a new government. Unknown to K\u00e1rolyi, however, the Social Democrats had merged with the [[Hungarian Communist Party]]; the latter promised that the [[Russian Soviet Federative Socialist Republic|Russian SFSR]] would help Hungary to restore its [[Greater Hungary (political concept)|original borders]]. Although the Social Democrats held a majority in the newly merged Hungarian Socialist Party, the communists led by [[B\u00e9la Kun]] immediately seized control and announced the establishment of the [[Hungarian Soviet Republic]] on 21 March 1919.\n\n=== Re-establishment and dissolution ===\nAfter the fall of the Soviet Republic on 1 August 1919, a social democratic government\u2014the so-called \"trade union government\"\u2014came to power under the leadership of [[Gyula Peidl]].<ref>{{cite book|last=Romsics|first=I.|date=2004|title=Magyarorsz\u00e1g t\u00f6rt\u00e9nete a XX. sz\u00e1zadban|location=Budapest|publisher=Osiris Kiad\u00f3|lang=hu|isbn=963-389-590-1|page=132}}</ref> A decree was issued on 2 August restoring the form of government and the official state name back to \"People's Republic\".<ref name=\"august2\"/> During its brief existence, the Peidl government began to abrogate the edicts passed by the Communist regime.<ref>{{cite book|title=Minisztertan\u00e1csi jegyz\u0151k\u00f6nyvek: 1919. augusztus 3.|publisher=DigitArchiv|page=6|lang=hu}}</ref>\n\nOn 6 August, [[Istv\u00e1n Friedrich]], leader of the White House Comrades Association\u2014a right-wing, [[counter-revolutionary]] group\u2014seized power in a bloodless coup with the backing of the [[Romanian Land Forces|Royal Romanian Army]].<ref name=\"P\u00f6l\u00f6skei\"/> The next day, [[Archduke Joseph August of Austria|Joseph August]] declared himself [[regent of Hungary]]\u2014he held the position until 23 August, when he was forced to resign<ref>{{cite web|title=Die amtliche Meldung \u00fcber den R\u00fccktritt|publisher=[[Neue Freie Presse]], Morgenblatt|date=1919-08-24|page=2|language=German|url=http://anno.onb.ac.at/cgi-content/anno?apm=0&aid=nfp&datum=19190824&seite=2&zoom=2}}</ref>\u2014and appointed Friedrich as Prime Minister. The state was formally dissolved by the new government on 8 August 1919.\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Hungary between the World Wars]]\n* [[Revolutions and interventions in Hungary (1918\u201320)|Revolutions and interventions in Hungary]]\n*[[Red Terror (Hungary)|Red Terror in Hungary]]\n*[[White Terror (Hungary)|White Terror in Hungary]]\n\n== References ==\n\n=== Notes ===\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n=== Bibliography ===\n* {{cite book|editor-last=Overy|editor-first=R.|date=1996|title=The Times History of the 20th Century|location=London|publisher=Times Books|isbn=9780723007661|ref=harv|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/timesatlasof20th0000unse}}\n* {{cite book|last=Rokai|first=P.|last2=\u0110ere|first2=Z.|last3=Pal|first3=T.|last4=Kasa\u0161|first4=A.|date=2002|title=Istorija Ma\u0111ara|lang=sr|location=Belgrade|publisher=CLIO|isbn=9788671020350|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=Sikl\u00f3s|first=A.|date=1988|title=Revolution in Hungary and the Dissolution of the Multinational State, 1918|location=Budapest|publisher=Akad\u00e9miai Kiad\u00f3|isbn=9789630544665|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite encyclopedia|editor-last=Tarsoly|editor-first=I. K.|date=1995|title=Magyarorsz\u00e1g|encyclopedia=R\u00e9vai nagy lexikona|lang=hu|location=Budapest|publisher=Babits Kiad\u00f3|at=vol.&nbsp;XX. pp.&nbsp;595\u2013597|isbn=9789638318701|ref=harv}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Commonscat-inline|position=left|History of Hungary between the World Wars}}\n\n{{Hungary topics|state=collapsed}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hungarian Republic, First}}\n[[Category:1910s in Hungary]]\n[[Category:1918 establishments in Hungary]]\n[[Category:1919 disestablishments in Hungary]]\n[[Category:1918 in politics]]\n[[Category:1919 in politics]]\n[[Category:Aftermath of World War I in Hungary]]\n[[Category:Former countries in Europe]]\n[[Category:Former polities of the interwar period]]\n[[Category:Former republics]]\n[[Category:Modern history of Hungary]]\n[[Category:States and territories established in 1918]]\n[[Category:States and territories disestablished in 1919]]\n[[Category:States succeeding Austria-Hungary]]\n", "text_old": "{{Distinguish|text=the [[Hungarian People's Republic|Hungarian People's Republic of 1949\u20131989]]}}\n{{Use American English|date=March 2019}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2019}}\n{{Infobox country\n |conventional_long_name = Hungarian Republic\n |native_name          = {{native name|hu|Magyar K\u00f6zt\u00e1rsas\u00e1g|paren=omit}}\n |common_name          = Hungary\n |life_span            = 1918\u20131919\n |image_flag           = Flag of Hungary (1918-1919).svg\n |flag                 = Flag of Hungary\n |flag_type            = Flag\n |image_coat           = Coat of arms of Hungary (1918-1919).svg\n |coa_size             = 50\n |symbol               = Coat of arms of Hungary\n |symbol_type          = Coat of arms\n |national_anthem      = \"[[Himnusz]]\"\n |image_map            = Partition of Austria-Hungary 1919 map.jpg\n |image_map_caption    = [[Aftermath of World War I#Austria-Hungary|Partition of Austria-Hungary]]: {{nowr|boundaries as defined in the treaties, 1919}}\n |status               = [[List of states with limited recognition|It became an Unrecognized]] {{nowr|[[rump state]]}}\n |capital              = [[Budapest]]\n |coordinates          = {{coord|47|29|N|19|02|E|source:eswiki_type:country|display=title}}\n |languages_type       = Official&nbsp;language\n |languages            = [[Hungarian language|Hungarian]]\n |languages2_sub       = yes\n |languages2_type      = Common&nbsp;languages\n |languages2           = [[German language|German]], [[Slovak language|Slovak]], [[Croatian language|Croatian]], [[Romanian language|Romanian]]\n |government_type      = [[People's republic]]\n |title_leader         = [[Regent of Hungary|Regent]]\n |year_leader1         = 7 August 1919\n |leader1              = [[Archduke Joseph August of Austria|Joseph August]]\n |title_representative = [[List of heads of state of Hungary|President]]\n |representative1      = [[Mih\u00e1ly K\u00e1rolyi]]\n |representative2      = [[Gyula Peidl]]&nbsp;(acting)\n |year_representative1 = {{nowr|16 November 1918}}  \n |year_representative2 = 1 August 1919  \n |title_deputy         = [[List of Prime Ministers of Hungary|Prime Minister]]\n |deputy1              = [[Mih\u00e1ly K\u00e1rolyi]]\n |deputy2              = [[